        <section class="main-idea segment-opener" data-uuid="86e1bad5c3454cd78b327dc6474597be">
            <article data-uuid="1e71d21de59c4e4db05829981b03f3e7">
                <h4 data-uuid="93d6ca345a2244418fbbd7b38683b879">Main Idea</h4>
                <p class="main-idea" data-uuid="91637d4c11d94d82870c1419c3272791">Pro-slavery and antislavery groups clashed violently in what became known as “Bleeding Kansas.”</p>
                <h2 data-uuid="9a212b4f23ff466ba8482400649ef34c">Bleeding Kansas</h2>
                <div class="yellow-star-yellow-bar" data-uuid="e86a562792444c5eaf73a1fc04abbaad"></div>
            </article>
        </section>
        <p data-uuid="901360db1e2c40a8a20a33dbfd183f1f">By early 1856 Kansas had two opposing governments, and the population was angry. Settlers had moved to Kansas to homestead in peace, but the controversy over slavery began to affect everyone.</p>
        <p data-uuid="7169523fb99740a1b595150d08155c5b">In April 1856 a congressional committee arrived in Kansas to decide which government was legitimate. Although committee members declared the election of the pro-slavery legislature to be unfair, the federal government did not agree.</p>
        <h3 data-uuid="c820eb1015cc4d22a52550217d51b5f6">Attack on Lawrence</h3>
        <p data-uuid="a3524631a0b14c8ba3fd6e69cebb191e">The new pro-slavery settlers owned guns, and antislavery settlers received weapons shipments from friends in the East. Then, violence broke out. In May 1856 a pro-slavery grand jury in Kansas charged leaders of the antislavery government with treason. About 800 men rode to the city of Lawrence to arrest the antislavery leaders, but they had fled. The posse took its anger out on Lawrence by setting fires, looting buildings, and destroying presses used to print antislavery newspapers. One man was killed in the pro-slavery attack that became known as the Sack of Lawrence.</p>
